The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Wednesday, January 28, 2004 				 Cong split on parallel poll
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Jan. 27: The Congress governments in Maharashtra and Karnataka are taking contrasting views on the timing of Assembly polls.																								While the Maharashtra chief minister is against simultaneous Assembly and general elections, his Karnataka counterpart  though in two minds  appears to be getting ready for the eventuality.																								During his meeting with party chief Sonia Gandhi on Sunday, chief minister Sushil Kumar Shinde is understood to have conveyed his opposition to advancing Assembly polls to coincide with general elections.																								But Karnataka chief minister S.M. Krishna is said to be in two minds about early Assembly polls. He had last week indicated the possibility of both elections in the state within five months.																								He is credited with the view that the Congress prospects would be brighter if the polls are delinked. Yet, Krishna has convened an early budget session next week at which a vote-on-account is likely.
